    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Keyword mapping</strong> is the SEO practice of assigning one primary keyword (and 3–5 secondary keywords) to each page on a website, documented in a spreadsheet that links URL to target keyword, search intent, and on-page element guidance. It prevents keyword cannibalization — where multiple pages compete for the same query — and ensures every page on the site has a clear, non-overlapping ranking focus.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary keywords per page</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Secondary keywords per page</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3–5</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Without keyword mapping, sites with more than 20 pages routinely develop keyword cannibalization — multiple pages fighting for the same query — and content gaps where important queries have no page at all. A keyword map is the operating document that prevents both problems simultaneously.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is keyword mapping?</h2>
        <p>Keyword mapping is an organisational layer that sits between keyword research (finding keywords) and content production (creating pages). It answers a specific question for every page on your site: "What is this page trying to rank for, and is there any other page trying to rank for the same thing?"</p>
        <p>A keyword map is typically a spreadsheet with the following columns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>URL</strong> — the exact page address</li>
          <li><strong>Primary keyword</strong> — the single most important query this page targets</li>
          <li><strong>Secondary keywords</strong> — 3–5 related terms, synonyms, and question variants</li>
          <li><strong>Search intent</strong> — informational, commercial, transactional, or navigational</li>
          <li><strong>Monthly search volume</strong> — for the primary keyword</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword difficulty</strong> — KD score for prioritisation</li>
          <li><strong>Title tag</strong> — the page's current or planned title tag</li>
          <li><strong>H1</strong> — the main heading including the primary keyword</li>
          <li><strong>Status</strong> — existing page, draft, planned, or needs optimisation</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why one primary keyword per page</div>
          <p>Google allocates ranking signals per URL. If one page tries to rank for "CRM software," "best CRM," and "CRM for small business" simultaneously, the signals are diluted. Assigning one primary keyword per page forces clarity — each page has one job, and the title tag, H1, and opening paragraph all reinforce that single focus.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why keyword mapping matters for SEO performance</h2>
        <p>Keyword mapping solves three distinct problems that emerge as sites grow:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prevents cannibalization.</strong> Two pages targeting "email marketing tools" split link equity and ranking signals between them, leaving neither in position 1. A map catches this conflict before new content is published.</li>
          <li><strong>Guides on-page optimisation systematically.</strong> Instead of guessing what each page should be optimised for, the map gives every writer and editor a clear brief: primary keyword in title, H1, and first paragraph; secondary keywords in H2s and body.</li>
          <li><strong>Surfaces content gaps.</strong> When you map existing pages, the blank spaces in your keyword list reveal topics you haven't covered. These become your new content priorities.</li>
          <li><strong>Improves internal linking strategy.</strong> When every page's target keyword is documented, you can identify natural internal link opportunities — pages that mention a topic but don't link to the page that owns that keyword.</li>
          <li><strong>Creates accountability at scale.</strong> For sites publishing 10–30 articles per month, the map ensures the editorial team never accidentally creates two articles competing for the same query.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to build a keyword map — step by step</h2>
        <p>A keyword map for an existing site takes a different approach than one for a new site. Here's the process for each:</p>

        <h3>For an existing site (audit + map)</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Crawl your site.</strong> Use Screaming Frog or Ahrefs' Site Audit to export all URLs, title tags, and H1s.</li>
          <li><strong>Pull current rankings.</strong> In Google Search Console, export your top 200 queries and the page each query sends impressions to. This shows what each page is already associated with.</li>
          <li><strong>Assign primary keywords.</strong> For each URL, select the highest-volume, most relevant keyword from the GSC data as the primary. If the page ranks for nothing, select the intended keyword from your research.</li>
          <li><strong>Flag conflicts.</strong> Sort by primary keyword. Any duplicate primary keywords are cannibalization conflicts — you need to consolidate or differentiate those pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Add secondary keywords and intent.</strong> Complete the remaining columns for each URL.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>For a new site (plan + map)</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Complete keyword research first.</strong> You need a prioritised keyword list before mapping.</li>
          <li><strong>Group by intent.</strong> Cluster keywords by intent type. Informational queries → blog posts; commercial queries → comparison/category pages; transactional queries → product/service pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Design the site structure from the map.</strong> Each cluster of related keywords becomes a content hub. The highest-volume keyword in each cluster becomes the pillar page.</li>
          <li><strong>Assign keywords to planned URLs.</strong> Even before the pages exist, assign them a URL and a primary keyword. This prevents duplication before a single article is written.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Keyword mapping approaches by site type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Site type</th><th>Mapping approach</th><th>Pages per map</th><th>Review frequency</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
