                <td>20–500+</td>
                <td>Monthly</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>E-commerce</strong></td><td>Category + product pages, faceted URL handling</td><td>Hundreds to thousands</td><td>Quarterly + crawl alerts</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local business</strong></td><td>Service + location page matrix</td><td>10–200</td>
              <td>Quarterly</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Publisher / media</strong></td><td>Topic clusters with URL hierarchy</td><td>Thousands+</td><td>Automated + quarterly audit</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real keyword mapping examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — SaaS product (project management)</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Keyword map entries — no overlapping primaries</span><br>
          /features/           → Primary: <span class="uf-new">"project management software"</span><br>
          /blog/agile-guide/   → Primary: <span class="uf-new">"what is agile project management"</span><br>
          /blog/kanban-boards/ → Primary: <span class="uf-new">"kanban board examples"</span><br>
          /compare/asana/      → Primary: <span class="uf-new">"asana alternative"</span><br><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Conflict detected and fixed</span><br>
          /blog/pm-software/   → Primary: <span class="uf-old">"project management software"</span> (CONFLICT)<br>
          Action: <span class="uf-status">merge /blog/pm-software/ into /features/ with 301 redirect</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Example 2 — Local accountancy firm</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Service + location page matrix</span><br>
          /services/tax-returns/         → <span class="uf-new">"tax returns accountant"</span><br>
          /services/tax-returns/london/  → <span class="uf-new">"tax returns accountant London"</span><br>
          /services/tax-returns/bristol/ → <span class="uf-new">"tax returns accountant Bristol"</span><br>
          /blog/self-assessment-guide/   → <span class="uf-new">"how to complete self assessment tax return"</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Keyword mapping vs keyword research — how they connect</h2>
        <p>These are sequential steps in the same workflow — research feeds mapping, mapping guides content production.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Keyword research (comes first)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Discovers what queries exist with search demand</li>
              <li>Evaluates volume, difficulty, and intent</li>
              <li>Produces a prioritised list of target keywords</li>
              <li>Happens before any content decisions are made</li>
              <li>Refreshed when new topics or products emerge</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Keyword mapping (comes second)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Assigns research outputs to specific pages</li>
              <li>Prevents duplicate targeting across the site</li>
              <li>Produces the on-page brief for each URL</li>
              <li>Becomes the operating doc for the content team</li>
              <li>Updated whenever new pages are published</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for keyword mapping</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One primary keyword per page, strictly enforced.</strong> If two pages need the same primary keyword, consolidate them. Exceptions only for genuinely different intents on the same topic (e.g. "buy running shoes" vs "how to choose running shoes").</li>
          <li><strong>Match intent before matching keyword.</strong> The search intent of the page must align with the searcher's intent for the primary keyword. A product page mapped to an informational query will struggle to rank because the format doesn't match what Google serves.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with existing pages before planning new ones.</strong> Mapping what you already have reveals both conflicts to fix and gaps to fill — both are high-ROI actions before any new publishing.</li>
          <li><strong>Include the primary keyword in three mandatory elements.</strong> Title tag (near the front), H1, and first 100 words of body copy. Secondary keywords belong in H2s and throughout the body.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep the map living.</strong> A keyword map that doesn't get updated when new pages go live becomes inaccurate and loses its cannibalization-prevention value within weeks. Assign a map maintainer.</li>
          <li><strong>Link from secondary to primary.</strong> When a new page mentions a topic that has a primary keyword owner elsewhere in the site, add an internal link. The map tells you exactly which URL to link to.</li>
          <li><strong>Review for drift quarterly.</strong> Pages get edited, new competitors emerge, and intent shifts. A quarterly audit ensures your mapped primary keyword still reflects what's actually ranking on page 1 for that query.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — mapping without fixing existing cannibalization first</div>
          <p>Many teams build a forward-looking keyword map for new content but ignore the dozen existing pages already cannibalising each other. Google can't decide which of your three "email marketing tools" pages to rank — and it picks none of them, or ranks the wrong one. Audit existing cannibalization before mapping new content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common keyword mapping mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mapping by volume only</strong> — a high-volume keyword assigned to the wrong page type (intent mismatch) won't rank regardless of the content quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating keyword mapping as a one-time project</strong> — the map must be updated every time a new page is published or a redirect is implemented.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring secondary keywords</strong> — the primary keyword drives the H1 and title; secondaries drive the depth and breadth of content. Mapping only the primary leaves the page thinner than it needs to be.</li>
          <li><strong>Mapping the same keyword to parent and child URLs</strong> — a category page and a subcategory page with the same primary keyword will compete. Give each a distinct term from the same cluster.</li>
          <li><strong>Not sharing the map with writers</strong> — the map is only useful if content creators reference it before writing. Embed it in your editorial brief template.</li>
        </ul>

